# Custom DnD Class Design Rules

When creating or editing a custom class document, follow this structure. Use the vacant template below as the canonical shape; fill in each section without removing sections or changing the order.

## DPR Benchmarks (Damage per Round)

Aim for each class’s damage output to sit roughly in these ranges by tier (average DPR across official 5E classes). Use these when designing or reviewing core features, extra attack, resource spend, and capstones.

| Tier  | Levels | Typical DPR | Optimized DPR |
|-------|--------|-------------|----------------|
| **Tier 1** | 1–4   | ~10–12 DPR  | 20+ DPR        |
| **Tier 2** | 5–10  | ~25–35 DPR  | 40–50+ DPR     |
| **Tier 3** | 11–16 | ~40–50+ DPR | 80+ DPR        |
| **Tier 4** | 17–20 | ~90+ DPR    | 150–170+ DPR   |

When writing features that affect damage (e.g. Level 5 spike, resource spend, capstone), add a brief **Balance:** or design note if helpful so the class stays in the intended tier band.

## Class Axes (Level 5 and Power Curve)

Different class types get their main power jump at level 5 in different ways. Choose the axis that fits the class and design the level 5 spike accordingly:

- **Martial (weapon/unarmed focus):** Level 5 is typically **Extra Attack** plus one signature feature (e.g. Stunning Strike, Improved Divine Smite). Damage scales via more attacks and later via resource spend or scaling dice.
- **Full caster (spell slots):** Level 5 is **3rd-level spell slots** (and access to 3rd-level spells). There is no Extra Attack; the power curve is spell level (3rd at 5, 6th at 11, 9th at 17).
- **Half caster (e.g. Paladin, Ranger):** Level 5 is **Extra Attack**; spell slot progression is slower (2nd-level slots at 5). Damage mixes attacks and limited spell use.
- **Support / healer / controller (no primary weapon DPR):** Level 5 is often a **throughput or utility spike** (e.g. more healing per use, double-target techniques, better condition removal), not Extra Attack. Keep damage contribution secondary and tier-appropriate.

When in doubt, see **Official 5E Class Reference** (`Almir DnD5E/Official 5E Class Reference`) for how official classes handle level 5 and the rest of the curve.

## Required Structure

1. **Title** — `# [Class Name]` (e.g. `# Monk`, `# Potentialist`).
2. **Class Overview** — Exactly four lines:
   - **Role:** (e.g. Mobile skirmisher, striker / Adaptive striker, Martial Controller)
   - **Primary Ability Score(s):** (one or two, e.g. Dexterity, Wisdom)
   - **Power Fantasy:** One sentence describing the fantasy and playstyle.
   - **Design Notes:** Short note on resource model and design focus (e.g. short-rest recovery, control, etc.).
3. **Class Table** — One table, levels 1–20, with columns:
   - Level | Proficiency Bonus | Features | [Resource column if needed, e.g. Ki / Potential Points] | Feature Choices
   - Use `—` for empty cells. Proficiency Bonus follows 5E: +2 at 1–4, +3 at 5–8, +4 at 9–12, +5 at 13–16, +6 at 17–20.
4. **Core Class Features** — Two subsections:
   - **Hit Points:** Hit Dice, HP at 1st level, HP at higher levels (standard 5E phrasing).
   - **Proficiencies:** Armor, Weapons, Tools, Saving Throws, Skills (choose N from list).
5. **Level 1 core feature(s)** — Named feature(s) with a `> **Design Intent:**` line. Define the core loop (e.g. unarmed + mobility, conjured weapon + element).
6. **Modular / resource system** (if the class has one) — Name the resource, how it’s gained, max, and recovery (short/long rest). Add a `> **Balance Target:**` (e.g. comparable to Battlemaster maneuvers or Warlock invocations).
7. **Techniques, maneuvers, or options** (if the class has a list of named choices at level 2 or similar) — Include a subsection that **lists each option** with **name** and **effect** (one or two sentences or a short bullet list). Do not leave "categories" or placeholders only; at least a minimal set of example options must be fully described so the class is playable.
8. **Subclass** — Name and level (typically 3). List feature levels (e.g. 3rd, 6th, 11th, 17th). Optionally list subclass names.
9. **Ability Score Improvement** — Note levels (4, 8, 12, 16, 19) and +2 / +1 to two.
10. **Level 5 power spike** — e.g. Extra Attack and one signature feature (Stunning Strike, Signature Form, etc.).
11. **Level-by-level features (5–20)** — Every level that grants a feature (not just ASI or "Subclass Feature") must have a **named feature in the Class Table** and a matching **subsection** with at least one sentence describing what it does. Do not use a single "Scaling features (placeholders)" block; instead, define each level's feature (e.g. Level 7: [Feature Name] — description; Level 9: [Feature Name] — description; … through Level 20). Levels with no new feature can show "—" in the table and need no subsection.
12. **Capstone (Level 20)** — One named feature. Include a `> **Design Intent:**` or **Balance:** line (reliable but not infinite; no dead-turn scenarios).

